modules.name: Data.Functor.Polynomial
modules.comments:
Polynomial functors and bifunctors for implementing data types that
comes equipped with free `Dissect` instances.

children.comments:
`Const` has no positions for elements, making it impossible to
dissect them further.
children.title: <anonymous>

declarations.comments:
`Const` models non-recursive data constructors.

`Const Unit` can be used to represent data constructors with no
type arguments, while `Const Void` can be used data constructors
that do not exist at all.
declarations.title: Const

children.comments:
`Id` has a single position for an element, and unlike `Const`,
allows its dissection to be eventually filled-in.
children.title: <anonymous>

children.comments: `Sum` dissects both of its polynomial functors.
children.title: <anonymous>

declarations.comments:
`Sum` models choice between two polynomial functors.

`Sum` can also be nested to allow for more variants, although this
comes with the cost of having to unwrap several layers of structure
when performing pattern matching.

Note that the `Sum` of some type `a` and `Const Void` is the same
as just the type `a`.

```purescript
0 (Const Void) + a ~ a
a + 0 (Const Void) ~ a
```
declarations.title: Sum

children.comments:
`Product` either dissects its left element into a pair of the left
element's dissection and an element full of jokers; or it dissects
its right element into a pair of the right element's dissection and
an element full of clowns.
children.title: <anonymous>

declarations.comments:
`Product` models a pair of polynomial functors.

`Product` can also be nested to allow for more variants, although
this comes with the cost of having to unwrap several layers of
structure when performing pattern matching. However, one can make
use of the `(:*:)` operator for better ergonomics.

Note that the `Product` of some type `a` and `Const Void` is `Const
Void`, while the `Product` of some type `a` and `Const Unit` is
just the type `a`.

```purescript
0 (Const Void) * a ~ 0 (Const Void)
a * 0 (Const Void) ~ 0 (Const Void)

1 (Const Unit) * a ~ a
a * 1 (Const Unit) ~ a
```
declarations.title: Product

modules.name: Data.Functor.Polynomial.Variant
modules.comments:
This module provides a `VariantF`-like type specialized to contain
polynomial functors and to be dissectible itself. Likewise,
operations such as `inj`, `case_`, and `on` are also provided.

See also: https://pursuit.purescript.org/packages/purescript-variant/

declarations.comments: Inject a polynomial functor to a variant given a label.
declarations.title: inj

declarations.comments:
Attempt to read a variant given a label, defaulting to a failure
branch with the failing label removed.
declarations.title: on

modules.name: Dissect.Class
modules.comments:
Provides the `Dissect` and `Plug` type classes based on "Clowns to
the Left of bme, Jokers to the Right (Pearl): Dissecting Data
Structures" by Conor McBride.

declarations.comments:
The `Dissect` class describes a transformation from a `Functor`
into a `Bifunctor` that dissects a data structure into its
components.

Specifically, it takes a fixed-point recursive data type:
```purescript
data ListF a n = NilF | ConsF a n
```

And it's equivalent dissection:
```purescript
data ListF_2 a n m = ConsF_2 a
```

Producing the following instance:
```purescript
instance Dissect (T_1 a) (T_2 a) where
  right = case _ of
    Left NilF  Right NilF
    Left (ConsF a n)  Left (Tuple n (ConsF_2 a))
    Right (Tuple (ConsF_2 a) c)  Right (ConsF a c)
```

See also: `Data.Functor.Polynomial` implements combinators for
defining data types generically, giving `Dissect` instances for
free.

See also: `README.md` for a more in-depth explanation and tutorial.
declarations.title: Dissect

declarations.comments:
The `Plug` class describes how to take a `Bifunctor` dissection and
turn it back into the undissected `Functor`.
declarations.title: Plug

declarations.comments: Types that can be dissected are Functors.
declarations.title: tmap

declarations.comments:
Types that can be dissected are Traversable, provided that the
Monad has a MonadRec instance.
declarations.title: tsequence

declarations.comments:
Types that can be dissected are Traversable, provided that the
Monad has a MonadRec instance.
